    ("initget" .
        ((name . "initget")
         (title . "initget (AutoLISP)")
         (summary . "Establishes keywords for use by the next user-input function call")
         (source-kind . "AutoLISP")
         (alphabetic-group . "I")
         (feature-groups . ("User Input"))
         (supported-platforms . "Windows and Mac OS")
         (signature . "(initget [bits] [keywords])")
         (arguments . (("bits" . "Type: Integer\nA bit-coded that allows or disallows certain types of user input. The bits can be added together in any combination to form a value between 0 and 255. If no bits argument is supplied, zero (no conditions) is assumed. The bit values are as follows:\n1 (bit 0) -- Prevents the user from responding to the request by entering only Enter.\n2 (bit 1) -- Prevents the user from responding to the request by entering zero.\n4 (bit 2) -- Prevents the user from responding to the request by entering a negative value.\n8 (bit 3) -- Allows the user to enter a point outside the current drawing limits. This condition applies to the next user-input function even if the AutoCAD LIMCHECK system variable is currently set.\n16 (bit 4) -- (Not currently used.)\n32 (bit 5) -- Uses dashed lines when drawing a rubber-band line or box. For those functions with which the user can specify a point by selecting a location in the drawing area, this bit value causes the rubber-band line or box to be dashed instead of solid. (Some display drivers use a distinctive color instead of dashed lines.) If the AutoCAD POPUPS system variable is 0, AutoCAD ignores this bit.\n64 (bit 6) -- Prohibits input of a Z coordinate to the getdist function; lets an application ensure that this function returns a 2D distance.\n128 (bit 7) -- Allows arbitrary input as if it is a keyword, first honoring any other control bits and listed keywords. This bit takes precedence over bit 0; if bits 7 and 0 are set and the user presses Enter, a null string is returned.\n256 (bit 8) -- Give direct distance input precedence over arbitrary input. For external applications, arbitrary input is given precedence over direct distance input by default. Set this bit if you wish to force AutoCAD to evaluate user input as direct distance input. Note that legal point input from the keyboard always takes precedence over either direct distance or arbitrary input.\n512 (bit 9) -- If set before a call to getpoint or getcorner, a temporary UCS will be established when the cursor crosses over the edge of a planar face of a solid. The temporary UCS is reset when the cursor moves off of a face. It is dynamically re-established when the cursor moves over a different face. After the point is acquired, the dynamic UCS is reset to the current UCS. This functionality is not enabled for non-planar faces such as the side of a cylinder.\n1024 (bit 10) -- When calling getdist, getangle, getorient, getpoint, or getcorner, you may not want the distance, angle, orient, point, or corner to be influenced by ortho, polar, or otracking in the Z direction. Setting this bit before calls to any of these functions will temporarily disable ortho, polar, and otracking in the Z direction. This is useful when you create 2D entities such as a polyline, arc, or circle, or when you use the AutoCAD ARRAY command, which creates only a 2D array. In 2D-only commands it can be confusing and error-prone to allow 3D points to be entered using ortho Z, polar Z, or otrack Z.\nNote: Future versions of AutoLISP may use additional initget control bits, so avoid setting bits that are not listed here.")
                         ("keywords" . "Type: String\nSeries of keywords.")))
         (return-values . "Type: nil\nAlways returns nil.")
         (release-information . nil)
         (history . nil)
         (examples . "None")
         (url . "https://help.autodesk.com/cloudhelp/2023/ENU/AutoCAD-AutoLISP-Reference/files/GUID-9ED8841B-5C1D-4B3F-9F3B-84A4408A6BBF.htm")
         (guid . "GUID-9ED8841B-5C1D-4B3F-9F3B-84A4408A6BBF")))
    ("inters" .
        ((name . "inters")
         (title . "inters (AutoLISP)")
         (summary . "Finds the intersection of two lines")
         (source-kind . "AutoLISP")
         (alphabetic-group . "I")
         (feature-groups . ("Geometric"))
         (supported-platforms . "Windows and Mac OS")
         (signature . "(inters pt1 pt2 pt3 pt4 [onseg])")
         (arguments . (("pt1" . "Type: List\nOne endpoint of the first line.")
                         ("pt2" . "Type: List\nThe other endpoint of the first line.")
                         ("pt3" . "Type: List\nOne endpoint of the second line.")
                         ("pt4" . "Type: List\nThe other endpoint of the second line.")
                         ("onseg" . "Type: List or nil\nIf specified as nil, the lines defined by the four pt arguments are considered infinite in length. If the onseg argument is omitted or is not nil, the intersection point must lie on both lines or inters returns nil.")))
         (return-values . "Type: List or nil\nIf the onseg argument is present and is nil, inters returns the point where the lines intersect, even if that point is off the end of one or both of the lines. If the onseg argument is omitted or is not nil, the intersection point must lie on both lines or inters returns nil. The inters function returns nil if the two lines do not intersect.")
         (release-information . nil)
         (history . nil)
         (examples . "(setq a '(1.0 1.0) b '(9.0 9.0))\n(setq c '(4.0 1.0) d '(4.0 2.0))\n\n(inters a b c d)\nnil\n\n(inters a b c d T)\nnil\n\n(inters a b c d nil)\n(4.0 4.0)")
